. Morris wants to people to be aware of the impact of dumping garbage off wharves. He says it’s a major problem & out-of-sight shouldn’t mean out-of-mind.
. Morris & Porter also found a lot of abandoned fishing gear near wharves. In this video, you can see it still fishing.
. While it’s funny to see a diver riding a bicycle, it’s not funny that Morris & Porter found bicycles dumped in most harbours they surveyed.
. Morris & Porter recorded video of garbage as far as the eye could see. Note all the beer bottles & rubber boots.

. Most of the “modern” garbage Morris & Porter found was within metres of a wharf. Anything from carpet, rubber gloves & rubber boots to appliances like BBQs & stoves – even a washer with a full load of laundry inside.
. Some of the garbage is archaeological - dating back to the s. You can see pieces of ceramics, butter pots & olive oil jugs. But modern garbage can be more harmful.
. Morris & Porter surveyed communities over years during scientific dives. They uneectedly found lots & lots of garbage.

Each purse contains skate embryo that feeds on its yolk & develops inside over months to years!
Females lay purses on the ocean floor, where the horns entangle with seaweeds or pebbles & anchor the egg cases.
A Mermaid's Purse has a pair of long “horns” at both ends (curved at end), and is greenish-brown to blackish-brown.
After fertilization, each egg is covered in a rectangular, hard-shelled egg case called a “Mermaid’s Purse”.
